## The Budget Path That Actually Works

![Princess cut SI1 vs sub-threshold VS1 budget comparison — 0.90ct G-VS1 vs 1ct G-SI1 price, face-up size, and eye-clean rate side by side](/images/princess-cut-si1-sub-threshold-vs1-comparison.avif)

The conventional assumption is that the clarity ladder goes VS1 → VS2 → SI1 for budget compression. In a princess cut, that ladder stops at VS2. The real budget move is carat weight compression — and the [princess cut size chart](/princess-cut-diamond-size-chart) shows exactly why the face-up difference is invisible:

**The sub-threshold strategy:**

| Stone | Price | Face-Up Size | Eye-Clean | vs 1ct G-SI1 |
|---|---|---|---|---|
| 1.00ct G-SI1 Ideal Princess | ~$1,800 | 5.5mm × 5.5mm | 10–30% | Reference |
| 0.90ct G-VS1 Ideal Princess | ~$2,100–$2,300 | ~5.3mm × 5.3mm | 98–99% | −0.2mm — invisible on hand |
| 0.95ct G-VS2 Ideal Princess | ~$1,900–$2,100 | ~5.4mm × 5.4mm | 40–60% with cert | −0.1mm — invisible on hand |

The 0.90ct G-VS1 costs $300–$500 more than a 1ct G-SI1, delivers a stone that is 0.2mm smaller face-up — the width of two human hairs — and has a 98–99% chance of being eye-clean with no cert review. See the [princess cut diamond ring under $3,000](/princess-cut-diamond-under-3000) guide for more sub-threshold examples.

Other budget alternatives that beat SI1:
- **Color compression:** [H color](/h-color-diamond) in a yellow or rose gold setting ([yellow gold guide](/princess-cut-yellow-gold-engagement-ring), [rose gold guide](/princess-cut-rose-gold-engagement-ring)) saves $200–$400 vs G color while maintaining eye-clean VS1 clarity
- **Lab-grown diamond:** [Lab vs natural price comparison](/lab-grown-vs-natural-diamond-price) — a lab-grown princess cut at VS1 D-color can cost less than a natural SI1 G-color at the same carat weight
- **Under $2,000 budget:** See [princess cut diamond under $2,000](/princess-cut-diamond-under-2000) — 0.75ct G-VS1 Ideal fits this budget with no clarity compromise

